{"parse":{"title":"Southern Record","pageid":33268389,"revid":730621772,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><i><b>Southern Record</b></i><span style=\"font-weight: normal\">&#32;(<span lang=\"ja\">\u5357\u65b9\u9332</span><span style=\"display:none\">,</span>&#32;<i>Nanp\u014droku</i>)</span> is a purported book of secrets describing the teachings of the tea saint, <a href=\"/wiki/Sen_no_Riky%C5%AB\" title=\"Sen no Riky\u016b\">Sen no Riky\u016b</a>. \n</p><p>After the death of Rikyu, the book was lost with its author, Nanbo Sokei, a <a href=\"/wiki/Zen_Buddhism\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Zen Buddhism\">Zen</a> priest and Rikyu's leading disciple. About one hundred years later, in 1686, Tachibana Jitsuzan, the chief vassal of the <a href=\"/wiki/Kuroda_clan\" title=\"Kuroda clan\">Kuroda clan</a> purportedly happened to find the book while heading to <a href=\"/wiki/Edo\" title=\"Edo\">Edo</a> with his lord. Tachibana set about the task of transcribing the work into five volumes, adding two further volumes when more documents came to light. He then made a fair copy of the seven volumes, and the book was named <i>Southern Record</i> for the first time. The collection was highly regarded as a direct record of Rikyu\u2019s teachings and exerted a great influence on the process of the concept building of <i><a href=\"/wiki/Wabi-cha\" title=\"Wabi-cha\">wabi-cha</a></i>. However, modern researchers believe that the book contains information not from Sen no Riky\u016b and regard it as a forgery.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Chapters\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Chapters</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Outline\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Outline</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Chapters\">Chapters</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Southern_Record&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Chapters\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<dl><dd>First Scroll: Memorandum \u5dfb\u4e00 \u899a\u66f8\u3000</dd>\n<dd>Second Scroll: Gatherings \u5dfb\u4e8c \u4f1a</dd>\n<dd>Third Scroll: Shelves \u5dfb\u4e09 \u68da</dd>\n<dd>Fourth Scroll: Schools \u5dfb\u56db \u66f8\u9662</dd>\n<dd>Fifth Scroll: Tables \u5dfb\u4e94 \u53f0\u5b50</dd>\n<dd>Sixth Scroll: Citations \u5dfb\u516d \u58a8\u5f15</dd>\n<dd>Seventh Scroll: Memoirs \u5dfb\u4e03 \u6ec5\u5f8c</dd></dl>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Outline\">Outline</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Southern_Record&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Outline\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>There are two opinions regarding the origin of the book's name. The first holds that it derived from the opening passage of the work by the Chinese writer, <a href=\"/wiki/Lu_Yu\" title=\"Lu Yu\">Lu Yu</a>, entitled <i>Ch\u00e1 Ching</i> (<i>Cha-kyo</i> in Japanese, <a href=\"/wiki/The_Classic_of_Tea\" title=\"The Classic of Tea\">The Classic of Tea</a> or Tea Classic in English), in which he writes \"Tea is a good tree in the south\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ref1_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ref1-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The alternative view asserts that it came from the name of the original author, Nanbo Sokei.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Ref2_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Ref2-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Southern_Record&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Ref1-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Ref1_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Volume 10, Chapter 3; \u8336\u8005\u5357\u65b9\u5609\u6728\u4e5f, \u8336\u306f\u5357\u65b9\u306e\u5609\u6728\u306a\u308a(cha wa nanpo no kaboku nari)</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Ref2-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Ref2_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"> Nanbo Sokei was the chief priest of Shuun-an of Nanshu-ji Temple in Sakai, Izumi Province (former Osaka Prefecture) and Rikyu\u2019s leading disciple. He is said to have just disappeared after the sutra recitation for Rikyu\u2019s second anniversary of death. Southern Record had been long lost since then, until it was found by Tachibana Jitsuzan. One of his most famous sayings from Southern Record is \u201cIf the roof keeps you dry, any hovel is good enough. If the food sustains your life, any diet is good enough.\u201d</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Southern_Record&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><span class=\"languageicon\">(in Japanese)</span>  <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.engakuji.org/\">Enkaku-ji Hakata</a>\n</p>\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1324\nCached time: 20180908203654\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.068 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.094 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 259/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 1464/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 379/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 9/40\nExpensive parser function count: 1/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1170/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.024/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.11 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   80.830      1 -total\n 33.99%   27.470      1 Template:Italic_title\n 29.95%   24.210      1 Template:Nihongo\n 22.69%   18.341      2 Template:Category_handler\n 19.73%   15.944      1 Template:Ja_icon\n 18.10%   14.630      1 Template:Link_language\n 13.46%   10.883      1 Template:Reflist\n  2.59%    2.096      2 Template:Yesno\n  2.41%    1.951      2 Template:Trim\n  2.35%    1.897      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:33268389-0!canonical and timestamp 20180908203654 and revision id 730621772\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[{"lang":"ja","url":"https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%8D%97%E6%96%B9%E9%8C%B2","langname":"Japanese","autonym":"\u65e5\u672c\u8a9e","*":"\u5357\u65b9\u9332"},{"lang":"pl","url":"https://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nanp%C5%8D-roku","langname":"Polish","autonym":"polski","*":"Nanp\u014d-roku"},{"lang":"ru","url":"https://ru.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D0%9D%D0%B0%D0%BC%D0%BF%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%BA%D1%83","langname":"Russian","autonym":"\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a